Update to support Puppet 5 AST

In Puppet 5, the AST changed dramatically mainly due to removing the
parent pointer 'eContainer' from the nodes. Also many methods were
renamed and their implementation changed slightly. 'eContents' became
'_pcore_contents' and eAllContents became '_pcore_all_contents' with
some subtlties that allow you to record the traversal path to each node.

This changes the parser_helper to return both the node under the cursor
and the path to that node. For Puppet < 5 it uses 'eContainer' to go up
the AST, and for Puppet 5 it records the paths using
_pcore_all_contents.

This changes the parser_helper to return both the node under the cursor

_pcore_all_contents.

Add types.EntrySchemaPredicate

The EntrySchemaPredicate will be used when optimizing wash find's
traversal. Idea is that the walker will only traverse satisfying paths
in the entry's stree. That work will be done in subsequent commits,
however.

commit.message:
Big cleanup: remove many things that I don't use

I have too many things in my vim config. There's a bunch of things that
I'm never using and it's just adding cruft and (possibly?) delays.

* vimspector is super nice and I like what it's doing... but in practice
  I've never really used it. My main interest for it was for debugging
  puppet code and it ....kinda works with enough tedium to get the LSP
  setup. But really it's super hard to test code because to make the
  catalog compiler traverse the code paths that you want to test, you
  need to somehow setup facts and vimspector and and the puppet LSP are
  doing nothing to help with that. I blame puppet-editor-services for
  that.

* vim-test sounds cool but in the end I got used to using the different
  commandline tools to run tests.

* automatic folding is pretty annoying after all. the first thing I do
  when I enter a file is to open all folds because they usually hide
  what I'm looking for.

* I actually never use snippets so that's a bunch of code and mappings
  that I just never use. also it adds to the visual clutter in the
  autocompletion from coc.nvim

* tabular is just not useful anymore for me. vim-puppet has had pretty
  good formatting for a while now and I can activate it with `q`.
  vim-puppet also does auto-aligns the rocket arrows `=>` if I type the
  symbol quick enough. so tabular just has no use case anymore.

* adding and not removing: vim-markbar is like vim-peekaboo but for
  marks. super neat

* nvim's "viminfofile" is called shadafile

* I'll give relativenumber another try. It's been a while since I tried
  it and now with number also set, I also get the current line's
  absolute number, which was what was missing before. I've also found a
  neat trick to only have relativenumber in the active buffer, and just
  absolute number in other buffers.

* the mapping for going to normal mode in the terminal is still a bit
  annoying. I'll try ctrl-n for simplicity, but I'm not sure if I
  overlooked something --- if it's something that I need in bash I'll
  have to remap again. it's a bit hard to find a mapping for that that's
  not going to be annoying since bash has all sorts of mappings of its
  own.

* coc-explorer is just way better than netrw, so I use that now instead.

(#21971) Create system for safely dealing with path patterns

Correctly checking that a given string is safe to use for looking for
files on the filesystem is tricky. This adds a class called
Puppet::FileSystem::PathPattern that encapsulates a validated path
pattern free of defects such as directory traversal '..' entries and
zero byte delimeters. This is then used to protect finding manifest
files in modules.

(#21971) Allow paths that contain .. as part of a name

The PathPattern code was incorrectly flagging paths like /tmp/foo..bar
as being directory traversals. This updates that to exclude those names
by checking each path component separately instead of looking at the
path as a whole.

In addition this fixes up the error reporting about these kinds of
errors in Puppet::Module by creating the absolute PathPattern for the
manifests directory of the module at initialization time, so that any
errors from it are not swallowed by the error handling for the relative
path searching of manifests.

This also removed some duplicate handling of init.pp and init.rb where
in the case of having no pattern to search for the init files were
returned twice and also seemed to be loaded twice. This does not remove
the behavior in which the init.pp and rb files are *always* returned
when they exist, because that seems to be explicit behavior added for
issue #4220.

(#21971) Allow paths that contain .. as part of a name

The PathPattern code was incorrectly flagging paths like /tmp/foo..bar
as being directory traversals. This updates that to exclude those names
by checking each path component separately instead of looking at the
path as a whole.

In addition this fixes up the error reporting about these kinds of
errors in Puppet::Module by creating the absolute PathPattern for the
manifests directory of the module at initialization time, so that any
errors from it are not swallowed by the error handling for the relative
path searching of manifests.

This also removed some duplicate handling of init.pp and init.rb where
in the case of having no pattern to search for the init files were
returned twice and also seemed to be loaded twice. This does not remove
the behavior in which the init.pp and rb files are *always* returned
when they exist, because that seems to be explicit behavior added for
issue #4220.
